For sale is a Hi Point 995TS with:

7 magazines

The rings are the perfect height for this rifle and I don't need them otherwise, so I'm throwin 'em in. I bought everything brand new in Nebraska; I'm the original owner. It has about 600 rounds through it.

I've tested many brands of ammo with this:

Federal 115gr (brass)
Wolf 115gr (Russian steel case)

title: For Trade:  1998 Infiniti Q45
postcontent:
I have a 1998 Infiniti Q45 for sale or trade.

 The Good:
 The car runs and drives great but needs some work. It has tinted windows (NH Legal) , and an aftermarket flowmaster exhaust done by Majestic Motorsports in NC so you can definitely tell it's a V8! It also comes with 2 Viper alarms both with lcd screens and remote start/trunk functions. I also had the alternator replaced in January of this year and have receipts for both as well. The A/C blows out ice cold air, heated seats work great, and aside from the work needed, it's a very solid luxury car on a budget. It has a NH inspection sticker that's good until November of this year but needs work to pass after that. 

 The Bad: 
 The car's title is "Reconstructed" due to a previous flood. I've had the car since 2005 as a daily driver and it has passed inspection ever since until recently. It needs a new O2 sensor,Vent control Valve,Valve Cover Gasket/s, and Knock Sensor replaced to pass next inspection. The dash may have a loose wire because it has gone out once or twice, but it doesn't seem consistent. Honestly with a little wrench time,a trip to Autozone, and some knowledge of a motor, the repairs can be done on a weekend. The air bag light has been blinking for years along with the seatbelt light, neither of which has ever caused it to fail inspection though. Non-Inspection related are the replacement of hood support shocks (or install a hood rod), and the sunroof very, very, rarely has trouble opening (could just be dirt in the track).

 I've included everything I possibly can so that there are no surprises. I'm a former US Marine and I believe in integrity and being honest unlike some people nowadays. I recently purchased a new vehicle and I hate to see this car sitting in storage. The reality is that after some work your looking at a very clean 98 Infiniti with low miles.

title: For Sale:  Colt Burgess 44-40 Rifle
postcontent: Many people were not aware that Colt ever made a lever action rifle but they did.  In 1883 Colt decided to produce a lever action rifle to compete with the Winchester 73.  Colt got their guns out quickly and made 6400 Burgess rifles before Winchester called a meeting with the Colt executives to show them the concept design for a double action revolver they were intending to produce.  As a result of this information, Colt stopped production of the Burgess and Winchester did not go through with their revolver plans.  This Burgess rifle is a real gem.  It is about 50% and is a 44-40 with a 26 inch barrel.  The serial number, XXX, indicates that it was probably made during either the first or second month of production.  The Colt Burgess is one of the rarest of the American lever action rifles and is not seen on the "for sale" list very often.

Building off the success of our highly-accurate and reliable OBR 7.62, we set out to apply the same proven design features into a 5.56 rifle. The result is a lightweight, and reliable, tack driver that remains cool…even after high-rates of fire. The barrel and barrel nut does not touch the handguard at any point, so there is very little heat-transfer to your support hand. Like its 7.62mm sibling, both the upper and lower are CNC-machined from billet aluminum, for the optimum fit and consistency...translating into maximum accuracy. Even though this is a complete rifle, the upper will fit to any Mil-Spec AR15/M16 type lower.

 The continuous upper-rail provides plenty of room for weapon-mounted night-vision day/night combinations and provides correct ballistic orientation for all inline night-vision combinations. The 10 MOA cant gives users an added advantage when using magnified optics at longer distances. A step-down at the rear of the receiver creates zero MOA for use of BUIS’s at shorter distances.

 Each rifle ships with three, 3” long, MIL-STD-1913 detachable rail sections that they can be configured anywhere along the entire length of the handguard (via threaded steel inserts), for the interface of MIL-STD-1913 equipped lights, lasers, bipods, grips, tripod mounts, etc.

 The barrels are available in 12”, 16.1", 18" & 20" lengths. They feature a 1/8 twist rate. All barrels are threaded in ½ x 28, with an A2 flash hider attached (other muzzle devices can be added at an additional cost). The 12” model have carbine-length gas systems, the 16” and 18” models have a mid-length, and the 20” has a rifle-length. Internals:
 The Bolts and Bolt Carriers are hand-polished hard-chrome with staked carrier keys. The carrier key contact areas fitted to allow zero gas leakage.

 LaRue accuracy is known world-wide. The accuracy of each LaRue Rifle is proven at our 100-yard tunnel using match-grade ammunition. No LaRue firearm can leave the facility unless it obtains accuracy of less-than 1 MOA (1.047”) at 100 Yards. Each firearm ships with a copy of a 3-round group obtained from that actual firearm. While we guarantee the rifle is capable of sub-MOA accuracy, we can not guarantee the end-user will be able to shoot sub-MOA…since we have no control over shooting proficiency, familiarity with the system, ammunition choice, environmental factors, etc. LaRue firearms are precision instruments that require discipline, training, proper ammunition and maintenance to yield the best results.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun is the new product from Turkish company Akdal Arms. This weapon is intended for civilian and security use, and mimics the famous M16 rifle in its layout and placement of most controls. It is remarkably light for its caliber and size, because of extensive use of modern, high strength plastics.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes conventional gas-operated action with annual (ring-type) gas piston, which is located around the support tube that runs below the barrel. Return spring is also located around the same tube, which is concealed by enlarged polymer handguards. Barrel is quick-removable from upper receiver, barrel locking is achieved by tilting locking piece inside the bolt, which engages the barrel extension. Charging handle is attached to the bolt and projects on the right side of the receiver. The upper receiver is manufactured from aluminum alloy; lower receiver, along with pistol grip and shoulder stock, is manufactured as one piece from impact-resistant polymer. Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes detachable box magazines, each holding 5 rounds; an M16-style bolt stop and bolt release button are incorporated into the lower receiver. Manual safety also duplicates M16-style, being located on the left side of the receiver, above the pistol grip. Here's the deal on him. 

He emailed me pretending to be interested in buying my pistol. After he got me to respond he announced that he was turning me in to ATF for "gun running". He also cursed at me, bragged about how he had "bagged" 20 people for ATF, was a lawyer, etc.

He has done none of these things. You can tell you're talking to someone uneducated about anything technical about firearms.

Here's the deal: he tries to intimidate you by putting your name in all caps. "I KNOW YOUR NAME JOE BLOW. I'M REPORTING YOU, YOU PIECE OF FILTH" etc, etc... Since no one here is doing anything illegal don't be intimidated by him. He has my name- so what? 

I had quite the email conversation with him. All he can do after you challenge him to go ahead and call ATF is to write long-winded, cursing insults about how you're inbred and a Baptist (OOOOOOOOOOO!!!!!!!) He is nothing but 1) a troll who is doing nothing but trying to rile people up and get a response from them, or 2) some dumb liberal who doesn't know the law and is trying to intimidate you. 

So just ignore him if you recognize the email addresses above. But even if he uses a different email, don't let him bother you.
